                            <comment id="12490271" author="kristwaa" created="Fri, 20 Apr 2007 09:45:42 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;This is my earlier announced test failure due to the &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/DERBY-2346&quot; title=&quot;Provide set methods for clob for embedded driver&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;DERBY-2346&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;DERBY-2346&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; commit.&lt;br/&gt;
The reason is that LobStreamsTest.suite was changed from running embedded only to both embedded and client/server.&lt;br/&gt;
Since the test is run both through the old harness and as a pure JUnit test, the two harnesses get in each others way. I guess both the old harness and the JUnit harness is trying to start/stop the network server when run in the old harness.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Note that the test runs fine as part of jdbcapi/_Suite (for &quot;all&quot; JVMs I think).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I would like some input on what to do with this. My take currently is to remove the test from encodingTests in the old harness, as that suite/test has been reported to be invalid (setting a read-only property to change the encoding).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12490367" author="myrna" created="Fri, 20 Apr 2007 15:06:16 +0100"  >
&lt;p&gt;Removing the test from encodingTests seems reasonable to me. Wish&lt;br/&gt;
there were a valid way to simulate the encoding testing in all&lt;br/&gt;
environments though.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/smile.gif&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Myrna&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12490445" author="kristwaa" created="Fri, 20 Apr 2007 21:16:02 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Disabled test in the old harness with revision 530903. Test is still run in JUnit (both embedded and client/server).&lt;br/&gt;
If anyone have ideas for running tests with different encodings, please tell!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
